pouch boundary-line patch 0004 - the pthread layer.

Phase 6 sub-chunk 9b (pouch-threads, pouch side). Retargets musl's pthread
layer onto Thylacine's thread + torpor + burrow-detach syscalls
(SYS_THREAD_SPAWN = 41 / SYS_THREAD_EXIT = 42 / SYS_TORPOR_WAIT = 39 /
SYS_TORPOR_WAKE = 40 / SYS_BURROW_DETACH = 38; <thylacine/syscall.h>; the
kernel substrate landed at sub-chunks 7-9a -
docs/reference/{79-sys-burrow,80-torpor,81-sys-thread}.md).

Eight files, one mechanical retarget:

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in  Adds four Thylacine extension numbers
      at the end of the table. The musl build's sed pass auto-generates
      the SYS_torpor_wait / SYS_torpor_wake / SYS_thread_spawn /
      SYS_thread_exit aliases that the source patches use. After a musl
      re-vendor, extend 0001's awk filter with four entries:
          m["torpor_wait"]="39"; m["torpor_wake"]="40";
          m["thread_spawn"]="41"; m["thread_exit"]="42";
      None of these are Linux syscall names; awk adds them as new lines.

  src/internal/pthread_impl.h  Patches the static-inline __wake and
      __futexwait helpers. Both bypass the futex op-code dispatch and
      call the torpor syscalls directly. __wake -> SYS_TORPOR_WAKE;
      __futexwait -> SYS_TORPOR_WAIT (indefinite, no timeout). Inline
      so every translation unit including pthread_impl.h sees the
      retarget without further file changes.

  src/thread/__timedwait.c  Rewrites __futex4_cp - the FUTEX_WAIT-with-
      timeout primitive every cond / mutex / rwlock timedwait uses.
      Translates musl's struct timespec relative deadline into torpor's
      relative microsecond timeout, clamping at LONG_MAX seconds (torpor
      further clamps at TORPOR_MAX_TIMEOUT_US = 1 hour per
      docs/reference/80-torpor.md). Drops the SYS_futex_time64 cascade
      (Thylacine has one wait-on-address primitive, no 32-bit time_t
      legacy). __timedwait_cp's clock_gettime + absolute-to-relative
      conversion above is unchanged.

  src/thread/__wait.c  Replaces the futex spin's SYS_futex FUTEX_WAIT
      call with SYS_TORPOR_WAIT(addr, val, -1) (indefinite). The 100-
      iteration spin loop above is pure userspace a_spin / a_cas and
      stays as-is.

  src/thread/pthread_cond_timedwait.c  Replaces unlock_requeue's
      FUTEX_REQUEUE call with a plain __wake on the source address. Loses
      the requeue optimization (waiters wake on l, race for r) but is
      functionally correct: torpor has no FUTEX_REQUEUE-equivalent and
      the contention cost is bounded by N waiters. cond_broadcast still
      serializes waiters on the mutex through pthread_mutex_lock's
      ownership.

  src/thread/pthread_barrier_wait.c  Same single-site retarget as
      __wait.c - the one inline FUTEX_WAIT loop moves to SYS_TORPOR_WAIT.

  src/thread/pthread_create.c  The lifecycle retarget. Three sites:

      __pthread_create()'s clone call  __clone() is replaced by
          SYS_THREAD_SPAWN(entry, sp_top, arg, tls). The new->tid that
          musl previously set via CLONE_PARENT_SETTID is assigned from
          the syscall return; the start-args struct lives on the new
          thread's stack exactly as before; TP_ADJ(new) becomes the tls
          arg directly (the kernel writes TPIDR_EL0 at thread eret).
          `stack` is 8-aligned post struct-subtraction; `sp_arg =
          stack & ~0xFL` aligns it DOWN to 16 bytes for the kernel's
          strict-16-alignment gate at SYS_THREAD_SPAWN. The clone
          flags arg is unused
          (Thylacine has no clone-flag dispatch; all pthreads share VM /
          FS / FILES / SIGHAND / THREAD group by construction; CLONE_
          DETACHED is purely userspace bookkeeping).

      start()'s body  Registers &__thread_list_lock as this Thread's
          clear_child_tid address via SYS_SET_TID_ADDRESS at thread
          entry. SYS_THREAD_EXIT atomically zeroes that word and torpor-
          wakes UINT32_MAX threads on it, mirroring Linux's
          CLONE_CHILD_CLEARTID applied to the __thread_list_lock
          spinlock. The sched-failure early-exit path (args->control ==
          3) re-targets clear_child_tid to &args->control before exit
          so the parent's __wait(&args->control, 0, 3, 0) observes the
          exit through that word. Replaces the for(;;) SYS_exit loop in
          that branch with the equivalent SYS_THREAD_EXIT loop.

      __pthread_exit()'s tail  The final for(;;) SYS_exit loop becomes
          for(;;) SYS_THREAD_EXIT. The main-thread early return - the
          self->next == self branch - continues to call libc.exit(0)
          directly (process exit, not thread exit; matches Plan 9
          exits("ok") via the SYS_EXITS = 0 mapping).

  src/thread/aarch64/__unmapself.s  Retargets the two-svc stack-teardown
      sequence. mov x8,#215 (SYS_munmap) becomes mov x8,#38
      (SYS_BURROW_DETACH); mov x8,#93 (SYS_exit) becomes mov x8,#42
      (SYS_THREAD_EXIT). The C-side ABI is unchanged - __unmapself(base,
      size); x0/x1 carry the two args; the SYS_BURROW_DETACH handler
      takes the (vaddr, length) pair the kernel attached. Used by
      __pthread_exit when a DETACHED thread is reaping its own stack-
      mmap region; the thread cannot munmap-its-own-stack via the C path
      because SP would dangle, so this asm primitive does both syscalls
      without touching the stack mid-flight.

The clone.s file (arch/aarch64/clone.s, the __clone Linux-syscall
wrapper) is left untouched - it's `hidden` and only called by
pthread_create.c, which this patch retargets to bypass it. Static-link
dead-code-elimination drops the unreferenced symbol from libc.a's link
surface.

Process-shared futex semantics (FUTEX_PRIVATE absent) are NOT implemented
at v1.0 - torpor is per-Proc by design (every wait/wake is keyed on the
caller's Proc *). The boundary-line code's `priv` argument is discarded
in __wake / __futexwait / __wait / __timedwait. pthread_cond_t / mutex /
barrier all run in process-shared mode by API but their backing storage
sits in pouch-anonymous memory (PROCESS_SHARED + a region mmap'd before
fork is Linux-specific; pouch lacks fork() per POUCH-DESIGN sec 8.3).
Programs using PTHREAD_PROCESS_SHARED attributes on cond/mutex/barrier
will compile + link but the cross-Proc semantics aren't provided.

PI (priority-inheritance) mutex paths - FUTEX_LOCK_PI / FUTEX_UNLOCK_PI -
are NOT retargeted in this patch. Those call sites in
pthread_mutex_{timedlock,trylock,unlock,attr_setprotocol}.c reach the
SYS_futex sentinel (0xFFFF), which returns -ENOSYS. A program that calls
pthread_mutexattr_setprotocol(PRIO_INHERIT) will get the failure at that
attr-set call; runtime PI lock attempts simply degrade. POUCH-DESIGN sec
7 declines PI as deferred-from-v1.0.

Binding design: docs/POUCH-DESIGN.md sections 7 + 14 (sub-chunk 9b).
Invariants: P-1 (no Linux syscalls reach the kernel), P-3 (every POSIX
call either works or returns a documented errno), P-4 (boundary line
holds - only src/thread/ and src/internal/pthread_impl.h modified; upper
half untouched). Audit-trigger: thread_spawn / thread_exit row in
CLAUDE.md 'Audit-triggering changes'.

